
# Project Rules & Coding Standards

## 1. Technology Stack
- **Framework**: Next.js 16.x (App Router)
- **Library**: React 19.x
- **Styling**: Tailwind CSS v4
- **Language**: TypeScript (Strict Mode)
- **Icons**: Lucide React
- **Package Manager**: npm

## 2. General Code Style
- **Indentation**: 2 spaces.
- **Quotes**: Double quotes for JSX attributes, single quotes for JS/TS strings (or consistent with Prettier).
- **Semicolons**: Always use semicolons.
- **Trailing Commas**: ES5 compatible (objects, arrays, functions).

## 3. Naming Conventions
- **Components Settings files**: `PascalCase` (e.g., `HeroSection.tsx`, `ThemeContext.tsx`).
- **Utility/Hook files**: `camelCase` (e.g., `useWindowSize.ts`, `formatDate.ts`).
- **Next.js Routing files**: `kebab-case` folders / standard Next.js names (`page.tsx`, `layout.tsx`, `loading.tsx`).
- **Variables/Functions**: `camelCase` (e.g., `isOpen`, `handleClick`).
- **Constants**: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` (e.g., `MAX_GUESTS`).
- **Interfaces/Types**: `PascalCase` (e.g., `UserInterface`, `HeroProps`).
  - Do NOT prefix with `I` (e.g., avoid `IUser`).

## 4. TypeScript Best Practices
- **Strict Typing**: No `any`. Use `unknown` if necessary and cast safely.
- **Interfaces vs Types**: Prefer `interface` for object definitions and `type` for unions/primitives.
- **Props**: Define props as an interface named `[ComponentName]Props`.
  ```tsx
  interface HeroSectionProps {
    title: string;
    isVisible?: boolean;
  }
  ```
- **Event Handlers**: Type events explicitly when needed (e.g., `React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>`).
- **Path Aliases**: Use `@/` for imports (e.g., `import X from '@/components/X'`).

## 5. React & Next.js Best Practices
- **App Router**:
  - Use **Server Components** by default.
  - Add `"use client"` only for interaction (hooks, event listeners) or browser-only APIs.
- **Functional Components**: Use `function` or `const` arrow functions.
  ```tsx
  // Preferred
  export default function HeroSection({ title }: HeroSectionProps) { ... }
  ```
- **Hooks**: Place hooks at the top level. Custom hooks must start with `use`.
- **Dependencies**: Ensure `useEffect` dependency arrays are exhaustive.
- **Images**: Always use `next/image` with defined width/height or `fill`.

## 6. Tailwind CSS Standards
- **Utility First**: Use utility classes over custom CSS files.
- **Ordering**: Follow a logical order (Layout -> Box Model -> Typography -> Visual -> Misc) or use `prettier-plugin-tailwindcss`.
- **Responsive**: Mobile-first approach. (e.g., `w-full md:w-1/2`).
- **Dark Mode**: Use `dark:` modifier if dark mode is enabled.
- **Global Styles**: Put global resets/fonts in `globals.css` but avoid component-specific styles there.

## 7. Component Structure
- **File Organization**:
  ```
  app/
    components/      # Shared components
      HeroSection.tsx
    (pages)/         # Route groups
    page.tsx         # Route page
  ```
- **Exports**: Use named exports or default exports consistently (default preferred for Pages/Components).
- **Hardcoding**: move magic strings/configs to `config.json` or constants files if reused.

## 8. State Management
- **URL State**: specific filter/search state should be in URL (`searchParams`) to be shareable.
- **Server State**: mutations should use Server Actions where appropriate.
- **Client State**: `useState` / `useReducer` for UI toggles.

## 9. Accessibility (a11y)
- **Semantic HTML**: Use `<main>`, `<section>`, `<header>`, `<footer>`, `<button>` appropriately.
- **Images**: All `<img>` / `<Image>` tags must have descriptive `alt` text.
- **Interactive**: Ensure buttons have `aria-label` if they contain only icons.
